1
00:00:01.180 --> 00:00:04.360
In today's Signal of the Day,
we have a look at

2
00:00:04.360 --> 00:00:09.570
an important problem in room acoustics
entitled Can One Hear the Shape of a Room?

3
00:00:11.270 --> 00:00:16.280
Let us first investigate how sound
propagates in a room between a sender, or

4
00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:21.220
a loud speaker, s, and
the receiver, or a microphone, r.

5
00:00:21.220 --> 00:00:23.340
Which is illustrated in
the following figure.

6
00:00:24.620 --> 00:00:27.360
The first sound to reach
the microphone corresponds to

7
00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:30.820
the direct transmission
path depicted in orange.

8
00:00:33.820 --> 00:00:38.290
But together with this direct transmission
echos from the walls also arrive at

9
00:00:38.290 --> 00:00:40.919
the microphone depicted in purple here.

10
00:00:42.030 --> 00:00:44.350
So walls act essentially as mirrors.

11
00:00:44.350 --> 00:00:48.350
Every time a sound hits the wall,
part of the sound is reflected in

12
00:00:48.350 --> 00:00:53.270
such a way that the incident's
angle equals the reflection angle.

13
00:00:53.270 --> 00:00:58.340
These angles are defined with respect
to the normal of the walls ni and

14
00:00:58.340 --> 00:01:00.820
nj, respectively.

15
00:01:00.820 --> 00:01:05.000
Part of the signal is also absorbed by
the wall which depends on the type of

16
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:07.790
material the wall is made of.

17
00:01:07.790 --> 00:01:11.110
The energy absorbed by the wall
is transformed into heat,

18
00:01:11.110 --> 00:01:14.730
which increases the wall's
temperature very slightly.

19
00:01:14.730 --> 00:01:19.080
This phenomenon is generally
referred to as diffuse reflection.

20
00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:23.620
These echoes act as virtual
sources of the original source.

21
00:01:23.620 --> 00:01:26.380
For example, here it's a virtual
source which corresponds to

22
00:01:26.380 --> 00:01:30.990
the reflection with respect to
this wall and here is a second

23
00:01:30.990 --> 00:01:34.890
virtual source corresponding
to the reflection given here.

24
00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:38.680
Echos generate themselves,

25
00:01:38.680 --> 00:01:43.090
new echos from other walls that
we call higher generation echos.

26
00:01:43.090 --> 00:01:47.670
And this goes on and on until the energy
of the signal is fully absorbed.

27
00:01:47.670 --> 00:01:52.530
The line in green represents, for
example, a second generation echo.

28
00:01:52.530 --> 00:01:54.280
First echo here.

29
00:01:54.280 --> 00:01:56.710
This point, second here.

30
00:01:56.710 --> 00:01:59.999
And this corresponds to
a second order in each source,

31
00:01:59.999 --> 00:02:02.080
until it reaches the microphone.

32
00:02:03.330 --> 00:02:08.630
We can now look at the simulation of how
sound propagates inside a complex room.

33
00:02:08.630 --> 00:02:13.958
This cool video was produced by one of
our lab members, Dick Schroeder, and

34
00:02:13.958 --> 00:02:18.370
illustrates how a pulse emitted
at a loud speaker propagates in

35
00:02:18.370 --> 00:02:21.548
room until all the pulse
energy is dissipated

36
00:02:31.612 --> 00:02:36.207
From our explanation, it seems that
sounds propagation is a fairly complex

37
00:02:36.207 --> 00:02:41.018
phenomenon involving the super position
of a signal and its different echoes,

38
00:02:41.018 --> 00:02:45.450
such that the derivation of
a model might not be very simple.

39
00:02:45.450 --> 00:02:47.640
Nevertheless, in room acoustics,

40
00:02:47.640 --> 00:02:51.840
sound levels are low such that the Linear
model is a good approximation.

41
00:02:53.080 --> 00:02:55.540
From what we have just learned in class,

42
00:02:55.540 --> 00:03:01.190
a linear time invarying system is entirely
characterized by its impulse response.

43
00:03:01.190 --> 00:03:05.230
By definition, the response of
the system to an impulse signal.

44
00:03:06.860 --> 00:03:11.180
We introduce by analogy the concept
of a room impulse response.

45
00:03:11.180 --> 00:03:16.860
So describes the audio channel between
the sender S and the receiver R.

46
00:03:16.860 --> 00:03:21.500
So room impulse response simply sums
up the direct path transmission and

47
00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:23.920
the subsequent attenuated echos.

48
00:03:25.370 --> 00:03:29.200
Let us now look at different
room impulse responses.

49
00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:32.130
For example,
the one of our lab conference room.

50
00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:37.910
Here we plot, on the top, the first
second of the room impulse response.

51
00:03:37.910 --> 00:03:41.960
And we also zoom in to the first
70 milliseconds at the bottom.

52
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:47.020
We observe that the early part of the room
impulse response contains more or

53
00:03:47.020 --> 00:03:52.110
less isolated well pronounced peaks
that correspond to individual echos.

54
00:03:53.110 --> 00:03:56.590
But non-flat fading,
diffusivity of reflections and

55
00:03:56.590 --> 00:03:59.760
the diffraction all unite
in the latter part of

56
00:03:59.760 --> 00:04:04.940
the room impulse response to create
noise like exponential decay.

57
00:04:04.940 --> 00:04:07.840
Of course,
an equally important contribution is from

58
00:04:07.840 --> 00:04:12.640
the fact that echoes get denser and
denser as time passes.

59
00:04:12.640 --> 00:04:17.090
The rate of the decay varies
wildly between different rooms and

60
00:04:17.090 --> 00:04:21.230
is linked to the so-called
reverberation time or P60.

61
00:04:22.510 --> 00:04:29.220
Which is defined as a time for reflections
of a direct signal to decay by 60 DB.

62
00:04:29.220 --> 00:04:33.620
It varies from around a second in
a speech-only lecture hall to about two

63
00:04:33.620 --> 00:04:37.040
seconds for
a general purpose auditorium, to for

64
00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:41.350
example, more than eight seconds in
the Notre Dame cathedral in Paris.

65
00:04:42.870 --> 00:04:46.180
It is a very good idea to listen
to room impulse responses.

66
00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:47.010
By doing that,

67
00:04:47.010 --> 00:04:51.332
we can really appreciate the difference
between various acoustic spaces.

