question of interest.

117
00:08:10.680 --> 00:08:13.340
Can one hear the shape of the room?

118
00:08:13.340 --> 00:08:18.620
The question is whether we can reconstruct
the shape of the room using only echos.

119
00:08:18.620 --> 00:08:21.930
Consider the following
experimental set up.

120
00:08:21.930 --> 00:08:24.230
We put some microphones into a room.

121
00:08:24.230 --> 00:08:28.240
We would like to reconstruct the room's
shape from what the microphones record

122
00:08:28.240 --> 00:08:32.810
when we clap our hands, that is from
the recorded impulse responses.

123
00:08:34.160 --> 00:08:38.050
Room impulse responses contain
peaks that correspond to echoes and

124
00:08:38.050 --> 00:08:39.919
echoes are muddled by image sources.

125
00:08:41.060 --> 00:08:43.240
But if the room is not too complicated,

126
00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:47.280
locations of image sources tell
us how the room looks like.

127
00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:51.430
So we can rephrase the room
reconstruction problem into a problem of

128
00:08:51.430 --> 00:08:54.350
localizing a certain
number of image sources.

129
00:08:55.580 --> 00:09:00.140
At the next level of abstraction we
forget that they are image sources.

130
00:09:00.140 --> 00:09:05.730
And we just attack a problem of localizing
multiple sources and meeting impulses.

131
